@article{Bradley2001,
abstract = {Levels of sequence variation in mitochondrial cytochrome-b gene were examined to as-certain if this molecule can provide a reference point in making decisions concerning species-level distinctions. DNA-sequence data from 4 genera of rodents (Neotoma, Rei-throdontomys, Peromyscus, and Sigmodon) and 7 genera of bats (Artibeus, Carollia, Chiro-derma, Dermanura, Glossophaga, Rhinophylla, and Uroderma), including recognized sister species, were examined to develop hypotheses for evaluating levels of sequence variation. Several patterns associated with DNA-sequence variation emerged from this study. Specif-ically, genetic distance values Ͻ2{\%} were indicative of intraspecific variation; values be-tween 2 and 11{\%} had a high probability of being indicative of conspecific populations or valid species and merit additional study concerning specific status; and values Ͼ11{\%} were indicative of specific recognition. It appears that genetic distance values may be useful for determination of species boundaries under the framework of the Genetic Species Concept.},
